data.survey.strategy: I tried to amass as many leads as possible to cross-reference with my team-mates, before filtering them
Just reading clues and seeing if anything "fit".
I looked at all the leads and created a narrative in my head about what may have happened.

I ignored clues about cars and clothing types, as these felt difficult to verify. I focused more on equipment used and more direct suspect information, such as criminal history and physical appearance.
I tried to categorize each name I saw and make connections.
Try to figure out which leads had the most connections to each other and to use the leads to make guesses about which of the other ones were relavent
I just tried to piece together clues, but it seemed to me that many were good leads so I was liberal with my choices.
Ensure logical consistency between the clues.

Based on the clues that were already in my list, I tried to match clues from other collaborators that would make a logical progression that would help me arrive at a conclusion that would help me accurately identify the suspect(s).
Went with my gut
I wanted to pick the more starnge person out of the group
I tried to put clues that were similar or about the same person together so I could look at them in their entirety more easily.
I tried to piece together all the clues into what made the most sense to me
Using collaborating clues as to perpetrator
Introspective; I tried to create the story with my selections.
comparing the clues that showed up and corroborated with each other
I treated everything as if it were accurate until proven otherwise.
i eliminated the clues that I thought would be false first and narrowed it down to who I thought was the most likely person to commit the crime
Take all the clues and see how they match up to what I was thinking
I found myself working against the timer more than the clues.  I tried to piece together the first feasible explanation for the crime from the clues that I could.
Connect the pieces of evidence and see which person shares all of them.
I tried to create a convincing story with the evidence. Anything that didn't fit the story I was creating went into the dead ends.
find longest chain of linked clues
I tried to start with things that seemed like facts, like things seen on camera or found at the scene. Then I tried to base promising leads off of information that fit with those facts.
I just tried to build up a case as the information came to me.

I considered clues that were mentioned more than once to be more promising--the more times the item (Warren, circular saw, etc.) showed up, the more I thought it would be relevant. Some clues really didn't seem to have any importance such as the man being ejected from a party.
Read all the clues and just tried to follow one line of thought
Review the clues and select those most likely to lead to an accurate answer.

I looked for more definitive statements -- things like "a circular saw might have been used" sounded less convincing to me than "there was evidence that a circular saw was used." Then I looked for statements linking the circular saw, for example, to other pieces of evidence.
I tried to use logic to determine which clues could be related and strung together, while also paying attention to what my collaborators were discovering.
I read all clues and then made a decision.
trying to fix what clothes and description went with what person
Based on reading the text.
picked items that sounded plausible and relevant
I looked for clues that ha at least one item mentioned that at least 3 other clues mentioned.
Evaluate the evidence and go with the solid leads
Dragged over what seemed plausible and ignored irrelevant things
Follow the clues and see which ones are most relevant to the crime of the stolen relic.
